<p class = 'introduction'>
    By now, you have seen how important a resistor is to an electric circuit.
    You can use a resistor to control the current of an electric circuit:
    more resistance will mean less current and less resistance means more current.
    Because current ultimately determines how, or if, most circuit elements work,
    it is crucial to make it just right.
    Beyond that, without good resistors, current will grow to high and produce a short circuit.
</p>

<p class = 'introduction'>
    But, before we can use resistors well, we need to know the resistance of each resistor,
    in Ohms. Unfortunately, they are way to small to write any numbers on!
    But fortunately, there is a universally accepted system of identifying resistance
    by using bands of color.
    In this pod, we will learn to read the resistance of a resistor by looking at bands of color
    across the resistor.
</p>

<h4>
    Reading Resistor Bands:
</h4>
<p>
    Each resistor has four colored bands.
    The colors are used to describe the resistance of a resistor.
</p>
<p>
    If you look at the four bands on a resistor, you will see three bands,
    a little gap, and then another band.
    The band that is after the little gap is the fourth band, which we will learn
    about in a different pod.
    The three before the gap are the first three bands.
</p>

